Reasoning: The paper examines coordination in a community of open source software developers, which is a classic example of computer-supported cooperative work (CSCW). The study also focuses on the role of knowledge transfer and the encoding of process knowledge in work artifacts, which are key topics in software engineering (SE) and social informatics (SI). The paper also discusses the importance of experience and the imagined audience in facilitating coordination, which are relevant to human-computer interaction (HC) and digital libraries (DL).
